ontainer_hierarchy><expanded_objects></expanded_objects><topic_dirs><topic_dir><name>Frozen Shoulder</name><link_title>Frozen Shoulder</link_title><description>Frozen shoulder (adhesive capsulitis) is pain, stiffness, and a loss of motion in your shoulder.  Shoulder pain begins slowly until you cannot move your shoulder at all. The problem occurs when the area surrounding the shoulder joint becomes thick and stiff. Frozen shoulder is more common in people with diabetes, thyroid disorders, heart disease, and Parkinson's disease. If you have frozen shoulder, your doctor may recommend painkillers, anti-inflammatory medicines, and physical therapy to help you feel better and regain movement in your shoulder. Follow the links below to find WebMD's comprehensive coverage about how frozen shoulder develops, what it looks like, how to treat it, and much more.</description><friendly_url>http://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/frozen-shoulder-directory</friendly_url></topic_dir><related_assets><asset id="091e9c5e8023e64f"><link_title>Tips for Taking Care of Your Joints</link_title><friendly_url>http://www.webmd.com/arthritis/caring-your-joints</friendly_url><thumbnail height="" width="" alt=""></thumbnail><collection_category_val>1006</collection_category_val><archive>0</archive></asset><asset id="091e9c5e80a02fe7"><link_title>Sports Injuries A to Z</link_title><friendly_url>http://www.webmd.com/fitness-exercise/sports-injuries-a-to-z</friendly_url><thumbnail height="" width="" alt=""></thumbnail><collection_category_val>1006</collection_category_val><archive>0</archive></asset><asset id="091e9c5e80659936"><link_title>Slideshow: Care and pain relief for bumps, bruises, sprains, and strains</link_title><friendly_url>http://www.webmd.com/pain-management/sprains-and-strains-10/slideshow-care-guide</friendly_url><thumbnail height="" width="" alt=""></thumbnail><collection_category_val>1008</collection_category_val><archive>0</archive></asset><asset id="091e9c5e8061af02"><link_title>In